Learning and Predicting from Video Game Sales History¶

A project by Martin Blurton-Jones for CMSC320

Why Video Games? \ While many see video games as just a hobby, or worse, just a mindless distraction, like many hobbies (and mindless distractions) there is a lot of profit to be made from it. Even within the relatively short existance of home video game consoles (having been only around for a little over half a decade), developers, ranging from independent programmers to massive companies, have published tens of thousands of games for people to play around the world. Video game development in itself has become a significant industry. \ \ According to this wikipedia article here, in 2017, the US video game industry is estimated to have about 66,000 direct employed workers, and over 220,000 employed workers when counting indirect employment. Additionally, in 2018, the US video game industry earned about $43 Billion USD, matching the revenue of the US film industry. With video games on the rise, it is important to understand historical trends to try and predict where the industry may be headed. \ \ Today's Goal: \ The goal of this tutorial is to use video game sales data scraped from vgchartz.com to try and make insights about the video game industry based on historical patterns, and eventually to train two machine learning models to make predictions about what video games would sell more than others.

Imports: \ The most important libraries we will be using are: \ BeautifulSoup, an incredibly helpful library for scraping data from html websites and reading them into nicer datastructures. \ Numpy, a library that provides many essential mathematical functions and processes. \ Pandas, a library that provides very useful datastructures for storing tables in rows and columns. \ Seaborn, an elegant and effective way to graph and plot various forms of data. \ Scikit-Learn, a powerful tool for implementing machine learning in a project, including everything from preparing the training data to providing models to train.

Parsing Onwards¶

The first step of analyzing data is gathering the data together. \ The table that this project will be using is available at vgchartz.com. \ \ Reading from the site: \ While BeautifulSoup allows us to read a lot of the data directly from the table into a nice pandas dataframe, there are some things about the table that make it difficult to do so. First, the maximum size for each page is 200 results, meaning each page must be parsed individually and then combined into one big dataframe. As for how many pages will be counted, that can be set with the pageCount variable (for performance reasons I reccomend about 10-15 pages). The next issue is that the table includes a consoles entry, which is a helpful piece of data to have about a game. However, each entry is actually a tiny icon that represents a console. To account for this, we can look at the url of the image that is called on each console listing, and then, using a regular expression, we can parse the part of the url that contains the name of the console.

#Define the number of pages to scrape (each page has 200 listings, there are 309 pages)
#Lower numbers are better/recommended if processing power is limited
#25 gives about 5000 listings (hard)
#10 gives about 2000 listings (medium)
#5 gives about 1000 listings (easy)
pageCount = 10

#Prepare the dataframe that will hold all the scraped data
vgData = pd.DataFrame()

#Go through the table page by page
for page in (range(1, pageCount + 1)):
    #Print out the current page to keep track of progress
    print("On page: " + str(page))
    
    #Creating the URL to get the current page of the table
    vgchartz = requests.get('https://www.vgchartz.com/games/games.php?page=' + str(page) + '&results=200&order=TotalSales&ownership=Both&showtotalsales=1&shownasales=1&showpalsales=1&showjapansales=1&showothersales=1&showpublisher=1&showdeveloper=1&showreleasedate=1&showlastupdate=1&showvgchartzscore=0&showcriticscore=1&showuserscore=1&showshipped=0')

    #Making the soup
    vg_soup = BeautifulSoup(vgchartz.text, 'html.parser')

    #Parsing the table from the page
    table = vg_soup.find('div',{"id":"generalBody"})

    #Reading the table into a pandas dataframe, labelling its columns
    pageData = pd.read_html(str(table))[0]
    pageData.columns = ['Pos','GamePic','Title','Console','Publisher','Developer','Critic Score','User Score', 'Total Sales', 'NA Sales', 'PAL Sales', 'Japan Sales', 'Other Sales', 'Release Date', 'Last Update', 'Misread']
    
    #The table uses small icons to represent which console the game belongs to,
    #So we can find each time one of the console pictures is called, read its filename, and then assign it to the right row
    consoleRE = re.compile('consoles/[0-9a-zA-Z_]+\\.png')
    consolepicsS = re.findall(consoleRE, str(table))
    consoleNames = []
    for i in consolepicsS:
        consoleNames.append(i[9:len(i)-6])
    #Replaces the empty Console column with the newly scraped values
    pageData['Console'] = consoleNames
    
    #Attatch this page's data to the main dataframe
    vgData = vgData.append(pageData, ignore_index=True)

#After adding each page, print the head of the dataframe to preview the newly generated table
print(vgData.head(25))

Tidying up the Table: \ As you may have noticed, the resulting table contains a lot of strange and confusing data.\ The next step is of course, to clean up all this distorted data.\ \ The first step of the cleaning is to get rid of some excess columns that contained erroneous or not very useful information, in this case 'Pos', 'GamePic', and 'Misread' which contained the position of the row in the original table, an icon for the original game, and a column of all NaN's, respectively. \ After those are dropped, all of the numerical sales values need to be adjusted. Each numerical sales value in this table is reported in millions with an 'm' at the end. So the function dropM goes through a column and removes the m and converts the remaining decimal into a float. \ Next, vgchartz.com links to reviews on some articles, which means many of the titles need "Read the review" trimmed off of them. This is an easy fix under the assumption that there is no game named "Read the review". \ Then, the next stage involves converting the reported release dates to datetime objects for convenience, however some values needed manual correcting because pandas' .todatetime reads the year '70 as 2070 instead of 1970. \ Finally, the last change is the removal of "Series" and "All" entries from the table, which both correspond to entire game series or multi-platform releases (individual titles are already counted on their own).

In [177]:
#These axis can be removed entirely as they serve no purpose
#(Pos is just the position in the table, Gamepic links to the game's box art which is irrelevant, and Misread is just erroneous)
vgData = vgData.drop(['Pos','GamePic','Misread'], axis=1)

#This function takes in a column name and for each item in that column it will remove the 'm' that indicates millions 
#and converts the value into a float
def dropM(col):
    for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
        if type(vgData.at[i,col]) != float:
            vgData.at[i,col] = float(vgData.at[i, col][0:(len(vgData.at[i, col])-1)])

#The dropM function is called on each column that represents sales in the millions
dropM('Total Sales')
dropM('NA Sales')
dropM('PAL Sales')
dropM('Japan Sales')
dropM('Other Sales')

#Removes the 'Read the review' tag that was added to each title where the website had a review avaialable
for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
    vgData.at[i, 'Title'] = vgData.at[i, 'Title'].replace(' Read the review', '')

#Converts the Release Date and Last Update values into datetime objects for convenience
#Also, because the years are only 2 digits, sometimes pandas makes assumptions like '70 means 2070 instead of 1970
#This corrects for that
vgData['Release Date'] = pd.to_datetime(vgData['Release Date'], errors='coerce')
for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
    if vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'] > datetime.datetime.now():
        vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'] = vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'].replace(year = vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'].year - 100)
vgData['Last Update'] = pd.to_datetime(vgData['Last Update'], errors='coerce')
#Remove any titles with null Release Dates
vgData = vgData.drop(vgData[pd.isnull(vgData['Release Date'])].index)

#This table includes some entries representing entire series as opposed to titles and it doesn't make much sense
#to compare individual game sales to entire series (the individual members of the series are included as seperate listings)
#It also includes some listings that amalgamate a game's sales across all consoles
#but this could interfere with speculation about consoles later on, so it is easier to remove said listings
for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
    if vgData.at[i, 'Console'] == 'Series' or vgData.at[i, 'Console'] == 'All':
        vgData.drop(i)

#Print the head again now that it's nice and clean
print(vgData.head(25))

Viewing the Industry as a Whole¶

Now that the data is settled, let's start by taking a look at the industry as a whole, as opposed to looking at individual titles, publishers, or developers. That way we can learn about general sales trends in the industry over time, get a better sense of the magnitude of the video game industry, and better understand this specific dataset.\ \ Calculating the Yearly Stats: \ Calculating data in terms of the year is a great way to measure the change over time. To expedite the process of totaling up several values for every year, the function "yearly_total(col, count)" will take in the name of a column and return a dataframe that contains the sum of that column for each year. \ The count parameter is just for a special case where instead of summing it just counts how many entries that column ha for each year. \ For example, yearly_total('Total Sales', False) would give a dataframe indexed by years with a column of the total sales across all titles each year. \ With this new function, we can calculate the total sales from games released each year and the total number of games created per year. \ \ Graphing the Industry: \ Once we have the means to calculate the totals, we can graph them to have a better look at them. In this case, we create a line graph of the total sales from games released each year, a scatterplot of each title's sales and release date, and a line graph of the total number of games released each year. \ What these graphs tell us is that there is a large climb overall, indicating there are more video games being released and sold as the industry grows. You may notice that there is a large peak just before 2010, which might seem to imply that gaming is dying out, but what it really shows is that our dataset is biased against newer entries, which have had less time to get and report clean sales estimates. Also, the scatterplot shows that there are several very strong outliers. Sometimes outside factors can affect a games' sales, for example, the highest point overall belongs to Wii Sports, which technically sold a huge ammount of copies because it was included with the Nintendo Wii.

In [178]:
#Generates a sum of the values in col for each year
#Count switches from a sum to a count of entries
def yearly_total(col, count):
    yearly = {}
    for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
        year = vgData.at[i,'Release Date'].year
        if not np.isnan(year):
            year = int(year)
            if not year in yearly:
                yearly[year] = 0
            if count:
                yearly[year] += 1
            else:
                if not np.isnan(vgData.at[i, col]):
                    yearly[year] += vgData.at[i, col]

    yearly = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(yearly, orient = 'index')
    yearly = yearly.sort_index()
    yearly.columns = [col]
    yearly.index.set_names(["Year"])
    return yearly

#Calculate the total sales from games released that year, then graph it
yearly_sales = yearly_total("Total Sales", False)
tsalesline, ax1 = plt.subplots()
tsalesline.set_size_inches(12, 8)
sns.lineplot(x = yearly_sales.index, y = yearly_sales["Total Sales"], label="Total Sales", ax=ax1).set(title="Total Sales per Year Across the Industry", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Total Sales (in millions)")

#Graph each individual title by its release date and total sales
tsalesscatter, ax2 = plt.subplots()
tsalesscatter.set_size_inches(12, 8)
sns.scatterplot(x=vgData['Release Date'],y=vgData['Total Sales'], label="Total Individual Sales", ax=ax2).set(title="Individual Title Sales", xlabel="Release Date", ylabel="Sales (in millions)")

#Calculate the total number of games released per year, then graph it
yearly_games = yearly_total("Total Sales", True)
yearly_games.columns = ["Total Games"]
tgsalesline, ax3 = plt.subplots()
tgsalesline.set_size_inches(12, 8)
sns.lineplot(x = yearly_games.index, y = yearly_games["Total Games"], label="Total Games Made", ax=ax3).set(title="Total Games Created per Year", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Total Games Made")

Understanding Regional Differences: \ Now that we've viewed how the industry has grown as a whole, we can take a closer look to see if there are any significant regional differences. \ This dataset includes three main sales regions: \ North America, which, as you might assume, covers North America, particularly the US, Canada, and Mexico. It is significant because of the US' strong prescence in the video game industry. \ Japan, which, again fairly self explanatory, covers Japan. Not unlike the US, Japan also plays a major role in both video game development and purchases, with possibly the most notable company being Nintendo, who has long been a major player in video game and video game console development. \ PAL, which may be less obvious. The PAL region covers multiple continents, ranging from Asia to Africa to Europe, South America, and Oceania. It was a designation that originally was used in broadcasting as those regions used the "Phase Alternating Line" television standard. Now many of the countries in the region no longer use the standard, as it was outdated (and actually significantly hindered video game performance), but in terms of video games the region is still based on the old members. \ \ Now that the regions are established, we can graph them. \ First we plot the sales per region per year. This graph shows us two things especially. One, that all three regions follow the same peak structure around 2010, which adds to the previous idea of it likely being a bias in the data as opposed to something like a spike in a specific regional market. Secondly, it shows the scale of each market, with NA being the largest market, PAL following second, and Japan ranking third. \ The second plot shows how individual titles rank in sales in each region, with the data once again showing the pre-2010 peak (which, the scatterplot shows is largely due to several high performing individual titles, such as Wii Sports).

Standardizing the Sales: \ As mentioned before, one of the most misleading parts of this data is the influence that a couple hit sellers have on the total sales. To combat this, we can standardize the sales with the mean and standard deviation to reframe each game's performance in relation to its peers, as opposed to raw sales numbers. \ The formula for this will be: \ $$Standardized Sales = \frac{(Individual Sales - Yearly Mean Sales)}{Yearly Sales Standard Deviation}$$

In [180]:
#Combines all the yearly metrics into one year-indexed dataframe
yearly_combined = yearly_sales
yearlies = [yearly_games, yearly_NA_sales, yearly_JP_sales, yearly_PAL_sales]
for x in yearlies:
    yearly_combined = yearly_combined.join(x)

#Calculate the yearly mean by dividing the total sales by the total number of games released
yearly_combined['Total Average'] = yearly_combined['Total Sales']/yearly_combined['Total Games']

#Grab every game for every year to find the standard deviation in sales for that year
for i, row in yearly_combined.iterrows():
    games = []
    for j, row2 in vgData.iterrows():
        if vgData.at[j, 'Release Date'].year == i:
            games.append(vgData.at[j, 'Total Sales'])    
    stdev = np.std(games)
    yearly_combined.at[i,'Total Stdev'] = stdev

#Print out the new yearly dataframe to check it looks right
print(yearly_combined.head(10))

#Calculate a new row of adjusted total sales
for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
    if not np.isnan(vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'].year):
        vgData.at[i,'Total Sales Adj'] = (vgData.at[i, 'Total Sales'] - yearly_combined.at[vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'].year, 'Total Average']) / yearly_combined.at[vgData.at[i, 'Release Date'].year, 'Total Stdev']

#Print out the dataframe with the new column to make sure it all looks right
print(vgData.head(10))

Clash of the Industry Titans¶

A large part of any industry is obviously going to be the major companies involved. The gaming industry is no different. People have famously joked about "The Console Wars," where people will argue about which company's console is the best. Competition like that fuels favoritism, and you would be hard pressed to find a frequent video game player who doesn't have a favorite developer, whether it be a little known indie darling or a name brand like Nintendo. Even just identifying industry leaders through sales can prove helpful for understanding the industry as a whole. \ \ Finding the Big Earners: \ First, I have defined a similar function to the yearly_total() from before, called company_total, the difference being it will go through a column and add to a publisher company based total. \ With this function, we can easily find the total number of sales per company, which can in turn be sorted to find the top 10 companies by sales. \ Having some knowledge of the gaming industry, many of the top 10 are not surprising, with Nintendo being a household name, Activision publishing the famous Call of Duty Series, and Sony being the developers of the Playstation, one of the top leading console brands. But the metric of total sales is fairly skewed, particularly in favor of game companies that have been around long enough to rack up sales (like Nintendo) or have developed far more titles than other companies (like Nintendo). We will revisit this later.

In [182]:
#Very similar function to yearly_total(), but this time it works with companies instead of years
def company_total(col, count):
    companies = {}
    for i, row in vgData.iterrows():
        publisher = vgData.at[i,'Publisher']
        if not publisher in companies:
            companies[publisher] = 0
        if count:
            companies[publisher] += 1
        else:
            if not np.isnan(vgData.at[i, col]):
                companies[publisher] += vgData.at[i, col]

    companies = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(companies, orient = 'index')
    companies = companies.sort_index()
    companies.columns = [col]
    companies.index.set_names(["Company"])
    return companies

#Uses company_total to find the Total Sales of each company, then sorts it to find the top selling publisher
company_sales = company_total('Total Sales', False)
company_sales = company_sales.sort_values(by='Total Sales',ascending=False)
print(company_sales.head(10))

Finding the Reliable Big Earners: \ As mentioned before, the metric of just measuring raw sales could be biased as some companies have simply released more titles than others, and by our current metric if a company released 100 mediocre games they would beat a company that released 5 really good games. Instead, we can take the average sales/game per company by dividing each publisher's total sales by the total number of games they have produced. \ \ After doing this, we can see that the list has significantly changed with new companies entering the list and some companies falling off. This metric better protects against companies that rely on just pushing out enough normal-performing games as opposed to reliably releasing high earners. However, several members remain on both lists, such as Nintendo and Rockstar Games (most known as the creators of the Grand Theft Auto series).

Predicting (or at least tricking a computer into predicting)¶

Now that we have a better understanding of the industry, we can try training a model to predict roughly how well a game will sell given some basic information about it. A model like this could be useful in the real world for predicting the potential success of a game before or during development (although from an artistic standpoint I really hope there is more driving the creation of a game than a computer telling a company they can make money). \ \ Preparing the Training Data: \ From the dataset we have been working with, it wouldn't make sense to predict a game's sales with regional sales data (because it wouldn't be much of a prediction more just basic addition). The model has to be limited to data that a game would have before or at least close to launch. The console, publisher, developer, and the release year can all be determined ahead of time, and critic scores are often released close enough to launch as critics get their copies ahead of time that its fair to predict from. \ \ To prepare the data for training, each of the aformentioned columns is added to a dataframe, and the console, publisher, and developer are all encoded with one-hot encoding in order to be compatible with sci-kit learn's models (this results in a comically large dataframe). The release date is simplified down to a year, and the critic score is set to 0 if the game does not have one.\ The standardized total sales (which are being predicted in this case) are labeled as "Strongly Positive", "Positive", "Negative", or "Strongly Negative"\ After all the data is prepared, the data is split into 75% training data and 25% testing data

In [185]:
#Begin preparing the X data by one hot encoding
X = vgData[['Console', 'Publisher', 'Developer', 'Critic Score', 'Release Date']]
X = X.join(pd.get_dummies(X['Console']))
X.pop('Console')
X = X.join(pd.get_dummies(X['Publisher']),lsuffix="Pub")
X.pop('Publisher')
X = X.join(pd.get_dummies(X['Developer']),lsuffix="Dev")
X.pop('Developer')
#Simplify release date to year
X['Release Date'] = X['Release Date'].dt.year
#Replace NaN critic scores with 0
X['Critic Score'] = X['Critic Score'].apply(lambda x: 0 if np.isnan(x) else x)
X.fillna(0, inplace=True)

#label the standardized sales to be guessed
def label_sales(sales):
    if sales > 2:
        return "Strongly Positive"
    elif sales > 0:
        return "Positive"
    elif sales > -2:
        return "Negative"
    else:
        return "Strongly Negative"
ts = vgData['Total Sales Adj'].apply(label_sales)
ts.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Splits up the data for training (75%) and testing (25%)
X_train, X_test, ts_train, ts_test = train_test_split(X, ts, test_size = 0.25)

Model 1: Random Forest: \ This model comes from sci-kit learn and works by fitting several decision trees to different portions of the training data. It makes sense for this goal because of the decent number of features being inputted into the model (random forests work best with more features). The n_estimators is optimized using a GridSearchCV.

Model 2: K Nearest Neighbors: \ This model comes from sci-kit learn and it works by identifying the k nearest datapoints or 'neighbors' to a point and classifying based on their values. It fits for this project because it accounts for brand value in that if a game is made by the same developer and publisher as a previous game, it is likely a sequel or in the same brand. The n_neighbors parameter is optimized via a GridSearchCV.
